## Headline

`docs/parity-criterion.md` records:

```text
current ✅ count: 49 / 50
target for 80% parity: 40 / 50
delta beyond 80% target: +9
```

So by the repo’s objective locked scoring, pipy is at **98% of the 50-feature Pi parity criterion**.

## What is green

### Providers: 11/11

Pipy has native provider implementations corresponding to Pi’s provider set:

- fake/faux
- OpenAI Responses
- OpenAI Codex subscription
- OpenAI Chat Completions
- Anthropic
- Google Gemini
- Google Vertex
- Mistral
- Amazon Bedrock
- Azure OpenAI Responses
- Cloudflare Workers AI

Plus **OpenRouter as a bonus** not counted in the denominator.

### Tools: 8/9

Implemented:

- `read`
- `ls`
- `grep`
- `find`
- `write`
- `edit`
- `edit-diff`
- `truncate`

Missing from production parity:

- `bash`

There is a `BashTool` helper in the tree, but it is intentionally **not registered in the production model-loop registry**.

### Core/runtime: 15/15

The locked criterion marks these as done:

- CLI entry point
- one-shot `run`
- interactive `repl`
- session persistence/catalog
- provider abstraction
- tool registry
- workspace context
- system prompt composition
- tool budget/malformed recovery
- `.git` default-deny/symlink defenses
- opt-in transcript sidecar
- JSON output
- provider streaming
- retry/backoff

### Resource loading: 8/8

Marked done:

- parent-walk context loading
- byte caps
- `PIPY_CONFIG_HOME`
- skills
- prompt templates
- custom slash commands
- themes
- image/binary attachment loading

### Advanced session features: 7/7

Marked done:

- session resume metadata reader
- compaction
- branching/forking
- export/share
- dynamic provider/model swap
- settings/config panel
- SDK/RPC-ish embedding surface

## The only objective gap

The single remaining red feature is:

> **B7: production `bash` tool**

This is deliberately deferred until there is a real shell sandbox. That matches `docs/backlog.md`, which repeatedly says production arbitrary shell execution remains out of bounds for now.

## Practical/product caveat

Even though the locked parity score is **49/50**, pipy is not trying to become a literal TypeScript Pi clone. The docs still call out product-maturity gaps/differences:

- no Pi `pi-tui` clone / full alternate-screen TUI
- no production arbitrary shell tool yet
- some Pi surfaces are implemented through different Python-native boundaries
- privacy-first metadata/session policy differs from Pi’s native transcript model
- command names and internal architecture intentionally differ

## Bottom line

We are **beyond the original Pi parity target**. The remaining meaningful parity blocker is **safe production shell execution**. Everything else in the locked 50-feature criterion is currently recorded as done.
